title: What to do in Milwaukee this weekend
text:
What to do in Milwaukee this weekend By Chris Foran of the Journal Sentinel Oct. 2, 2015 7:00 a.m. (0) Comments 
The Best of Brew City is your mobile guide to going out in Milwaukee. Visit jsonline.com/brewcity and download the app for iOS or Android today. 
You've played the game; now you listen to the music in a concert setting. "Symphony of the Goddesses — Master Quest" includes more than 28 years of music from the phenomenally popular "Legend of Zelda" video game franchise, arranged with both Link-heads and symphony-goers in mind. The concert is at 8 p.m. Saturday at the Milwaukee Theatre, 500 W. Kilbourn Ave.; tickets are $32.75 to $66.75. 
Info: milwaukeetheatre.com 
The dogs — and cats, and any other pets you can get to march along — have their day, again, on Brady St. for the annual Brady St. Pet Parade . Held Sunday from 11 a.m. to 3 p.m., the doings include contests (best tail-wagging, pet/owner look-alike, human barking) before the 1 p.m. parade, with the traditional pet blessing at 1:30 p.m. There's also live music, a raffle, sidewalk sales, drink specials at participating Brady St. venues and more. 
Info: bradystreet.org 
Sunday is Cider Sunday at Wehr Nature Center, 9701 W. College Ave., Franklin, in Whitnall Park. That means freshly made apple cider, apple treats, live music, guided hikes and other family-friendly activities. A variety of apples will be available for sampling, and for sale, along with a range of goodies for purchase (e.g. chocolate-apple brownies, for starters). The event runs from 11:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. Admission is $3; parking for the event is $3 per car. 
Info: countyparks.com or (414) 425-8550
